comments.body:
Here's an index count validation strategy:

```
new_index_counts = Spotlight::Exhibit.all.map{ |e| [e.id, e.resources.count]}.to_h.sort
# Do the same on the machine connected to the old index and copy/paste it into `old_index_counts`
counts_zip = new_index_counts.zip(old_index_counts)
counts_zip.each do |tt|
  if tt[0][0] == tt[1][0] && tt[0][1] == tt[1][1]
    puts "e #{tt[0][0]} equal"
  elsif tt[0][0] == tt[1][0]
    puts "e #{tt[0][0]} new index count #{tt[0][1]} old index count #{tt[1][1]}"
  else
    puts tt
  end
end; nil
```

The full reindex timed at < 12 hours on staging with both machines (3 workers each). We should run it again with a single machine and double the workers.

To double the workers on one box:

1. ssh to one box and `sudo service sidekiq-workers stop`
2. ssh to the other box and `sudo vim /etc/systemd/system/sidekiq-workers.service`
3. in the bundle exec sidekiq change the `-c` arg to double its value (from 3 to 6)
4. run `sudo systemctl daemon-reload`
5. `sudo service sidekiq-workers restart`
6. observe the change in the sidekiq admin panel

comments.body: I added the rubocop disable because I think at some point we may want to accumulate all errors and send them in a single email. if/when we do that we won't need the return anymore.
Make bulk update a database object?
Or manually requeue with an `alerted:` flag? I'm open to retrying not being useful at all here though, I just realized it'd only happen if something didn't validate.
It's already passing around a lot of arguments.

Yeah I don't know that there's a scenario where a retry succeeds without intervention. And if the person intervenes and then starts up the bulk update job again we still have the other one retrying which may not be expected.
Works for me.

comments.body:
@carolyncole very graciously paired with me, and during this session, it was identified that the PostgreSQL database server had been updated upstream within the Ansible Playbook, and that the owner for the database which had been migrated to the new PostgreSQL database server had retained the owner of the `postgres` user.

After correcting this from within the PostgreSQL database server environment to the owner `oawaiver_staging_db_user`, deployments now succeed.

comments.body:
In my case I had an rsa key and a id_ed25519 key. 
when I was trying to deploy with capistrano it was using the id_ed25519 and failing.
I was not able to set the desired order in the ~/.ssh/config file. 
Adding both keys in the ssh agent didn't make any difference. 
I removed the id_ed25519 and then I was able to deploy with cap successfully.
I couldn't replicate locally, so I edited the collection in aspace and immediately saved it, then forced an incremental reindex and it was fine after.
Closed by https://github.com/pulibrary/pulmap/pull/1086
